IRS990.MissionDesc: MISSION: INSPIRING GENEROSITY TO STRENGTHEN MINNESOTA COMMUNITIES.VISION: MINNESOTA...WHERE ALL COMMUNITIES AND PEOPLE THRIVE.VALUES: LEAD WITH RESPECT--ACT WITH INTEGRITY--ADVANCE EQUITY--EMBRACE COLLABORATION--STRIVE FOR EXCELLENCE--SPARK INNOVATION.
IRS990.Desc: AS MINNESOTA'S LARGEST COMMUNITY FOUNDATION, WE ARE A PERMANENT RESOURCE DEDICATED TO ADDRESSING CHANGING NEEDS IN MINNESOTA - FOREVER. WE HELP PEOPLE AND ORGANIZATIONS TO RESOLVE PROBLEMS AND ADDRESS COMMUNITY NEEDS BY WORKING WITH DONORS, PROFESSIONAL AND LEGAL ADVISORS, NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS AND LOCAL LEADERS TO IDENTIFY AND SUPPORT CRITICAL NEEDS ACROSS MINNESOTA. WE INVEST CHARITABLE ASSETS ENTRUSTED TO US TO ADDRESS LONG-TERM COMMUNITY NEEDS AND HELP DONORS ACHIEVE THEIR CHARITABLE GIVING GOALS TO CREATE A LASTING LEGACY FOR THEIR COMMUNITY. THANKS TO THE GENEROSITY OF OUR DONORS WE SUPPORT INITIATIVES AND PROJECTS DESIGNED TO ADDRESS COMPLEX COMMUNITY ISSUES AND BUILD CAPACITY TO MEET IMMEDIATE AND LONG-TERM NEEDS AND TO INSPIRE INNOVATION AND FRESH APPROACHES TO ADDRESS CHANGING COMMUNITY NEEDS. THE FOUNDATION ALSO SERVES 14 GEOGRAPHIC COMMUNITY AFFILIATES WITH GRANT MAKING, FUNDRAISING AND TRAINING SUPPORT. EACH AFFILIATE HAS A COMMUNITY ENDOWMENT FUND AND IS LED BY COMMUNITY ADVISORS. TOGETHER, THE AFFILIATES HAVE MADE NEARLY $20 MILLION IN GRANTS OVER THE PAST 25 YEARS THAT ADDRESS ISSUES SELECTED BY PEOPLE IN THE COMMUNITIES THEY REPRESENT. THE FOUNDATION ALSO MANAGES 700 FUNDS FOR INDIVIDUALS AND NONPROFITS

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: MINNESOTA COMMUNITY FOUNDATION IS A LONGTIME SUPPORTER AND PROPONENT OF INNOVATIVE COMMUNITY INITIATIVES THAT SERVE MINNESOTA. WE LAUNCHED GIVEMN.ORG IN 2009 AND CHANGED THE FACE OF GIVING IN MINNESOTA. THIS GROUNDBREAKING GIVING PLATFORM MOVED CHARITABLE GIVING ONLINE AND ATTRACTED MORE DONORS ACROSS THE STATE - WITH THE SIMPLE IDEA THAT MANY SMALL DONATIONS CAN HAVE A BIG EFFECT IN OUR COMMUNITIES. SINCE 2009, GIVEMN HAS SPARKED MORE THAN $140 MILLION IN ONLINE GIVING FOR SCHOOLS AND NONPROFITS ACROSS MINNESOTA. IT HAS INSPIRED MULTIPLE GENERATIONS TO GIVE TO THE CAUSES CLOSE TO THEIR HEART.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE MINNESOTA COMMUNITY FOUNDATION IS ACTING AS TRUSTEE AND ADMINISTRATOR FOR CHARITABLE REMAINDER TRUSTS.

THE FOUNDATION INVESTS THE ENDOWMENT FUNDS WITH THE GOALS OF PRESERVING THE REAL PURCHASING POWER OF PERMANENT ASSETS AND USING THE ANNUAL DISTRIBUTIONS TO FUND AN ONGOING GRANT MAKING PROGRAM THAT MEETS THE CHARITABLE NEEDS OF THE COMMUNITY. OUR ENDOWMENT ASSETS COME TO US FROM OUR GENEROUS DONORS IN THE FORM OF UNRESTRICTED, FIELD OF INTEREST, DONOR ADVISED AND SCHOLARSHIP FUNDS AS WELL AS FUNDS ESTABLISHED TO PROVIDE PERMANENT SUPPORT FOR SPECIFIC COMMUNITIES AND CHARITABLE INSTITUTIONS WITHIN OUR GEOGRAPHIC REGION.
THE FOUNDATION FOLLOWS ACCOUNTING STANDARDS FOR UNCERTAIN TAX POSITIONS. NO LIABILITY HAS BEEN RECOGNIZED BY THE FOUNDATION UNDER THIS STANDARD.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE FOUNDATION HAS ESTABLISHED A CODE OF BUSINESS CONDUCT POLICY. THIS POLICY COVERS THE AREAS OF CONFIDENTIALITY, CONFLICT OF INTEREST, ETHICS AND REPORTS OF WRONGDOING. THE FOLLOWING OUTLINES HOW THE POLICY IS BEING IMPLEMENTED: 1. ANNUALLY, THE VICE PRESIDENT OF FINANCE REVIEWS THE CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY WITH STAFF AT THE JANUARY ALL-STAFF MEETING. ANNUALLY, STAFF ARE REQUIRED TO SIGN A CONFLICT OF INTEREST FORM. THE VICE PRESIDENT OF FINANCE ENSURES THAT EACH EMPLOYEE HAS COMPLETED A SIGNED FORM BY THE END OF FEBRUARY FOLLOWING THE JANUARY MEETING. 2. AT THE FIRST MEETING OF THE YEAR, THE BOARD MEMBERS COMPLETE CONFLICT OF INTEREST FORMS LISTING THEIR POTENTIAL CONFLICTS. BOARD MEMBERS NOT IN ATTENDANCE AT THE PARTICULAR MEETING ARE CONTACTED BY A MEMBER OF SENIOR MANAGEMENT AND ASKED TO COMPLETE THE CONFLICT OF INTEREST FORM. 3. NEW STAFF AND BOARD MEMBERS RECEIVE THE FULL CODE OF BUSINESS CONDUCT POLICY WITH THEIR ORIENTATION MATERIALS. THEY SIGN AND RETURN THE FORM STATING THEY HAVE READ AND AGREE TO COMPLY WITH THE TERMS OF THE CODE OF BUSINESS CONDUCT POLICY. 4. NON-BOARD MEMBERS OF BOARD COMMITTEES REVIEW THE POLICY UPON JOINING THE COMMITTEE. THEY ALSO SIGN AND RETURN THE CONFLICT OF INTEREST FORM ANNUALLY. 5. FOUNDATION CONSULTANTS ARE GIVEN THE EXECUTIVE SUMMARY OF THE CODE OF BUSINESS CONDUCT POLICY AS PART OF THE INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR AGREEMENT.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 15
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE OFFICERS AND DIRECTORS OF THE MINNESOTA COMMUNITY FOUNDATION ARE THE SAME AS THE OFFICERS AND DIRECTORS OF THE SAINT PAUL FOUNDATION. THE OFFICERS ARE PAID BY THE SAINT PAUL FOUNDATION, WHICH IS A RELATED ORGANIZATION. THE MINNESOTA COMMUNITY FOUNDATION IS REPORTING COMPENSATION OF OFFICERS FROM A RELATED ORGANIZATION ON PART VII OF THE FORM 990. THE SAINT PAUL FOUNDATION'S POLICY FOR EVALUATING OFFICER COMPENSATION IS AS FOLLOWS: CEO COMPENSATION AND BENEFITS: THE SAINT PAUL FOUNDATION UTILIZES AN OUTSIDE THIRD PARTY CONSULTANT TO CONDUCT A CUSTOM SURVEY TO PROVIDE MARKET BENCHMARKING RELATIVE TO THE FOUNDATIONS' CEO POSITION. THE COMPENSATION SURVEY IS GENERALLY CONDUCTED EVERY TWO YEARS. THE OBJECTIVE OF THE SURVEY IS TO DETERMINE THE LEVEL OF COMPENSATION THAT WOULD BE CONSIDERED COMPETITIVE FOR THE FOUNDATION'S CEO COMPARED TO TOP EXECUTIVES OF OTHER NONPROFITS WITH PARTICULAR ATTENTION TO THOSE OF SIMILAR NATURE AND ASSET SIZE. THE COMPARATOR GROUP, CURRENTLY FOURTEEN LOCAL AND NATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS, IS REVIEWED BY THE BOARD CHAIR AND EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE. THE COMPARATOR GROUP REFLECTS ORGANIZATIONS WITH SIMILAR ASSET SIZE, COMPLEXITY OF WORK AND POTENTIAL RECRUITMENT MARKET. COMPETITIVE PAY IS DETERMINED BY CALCULATING A BASE MARKET INDEX. THE CALCULATION COMPARES THE FOUNDATION'S CEO BASE ANNUAL SALARY TO THE MEDIAN BASE ANNUAL SALARIES OF THE SURVEY PARTICIPANTS. A MARKET INDEX BETWEEN 95 AND 105 IS GENERALLY CONSIDERED TO BE MATCHING MARKET INDEX. BENEFIT SURVEY DATA IS GENERALLY COLLECTED EVERY THREE TO FIVE YEARS AND FOCUSES ON BENEFITS PROVIDED EXCLUSIVELY TO THE CEO AND TOP EXECUTIVES. STAFF COMPENSATION: A COMPREHENSIVE REVIEW OF STAFF COMPENSATION USING LOCAL INDUSTRY AND NATIONAL COMMUNITY FOUNDATION SURVEY DATA IS GENERALLY CONDUCTED EVERY TWO YEARS. THE OBJECTIVE OF THE COMPREHENSIVE REVIEW IS TO DETERMINE COMPARABLE MARKET PAY FOR INDIVIDUAL POSITIONS. FROM SURVEY RESULTS, THE MEAN (AVERAGE) SALARY IS DEFINED AS THE MARKET REFERENCE POINT (MRP). MINIMUM AND MAXIMUM PAY FOR EACH POSITION IS SET AT -/+ 20% OF MRP, AND PAY IS CONSIDERED COMPETITIVE WHEN IT IS WITHIN 10% OF A POSITION'S MRP. IF A POSITION IS UNIQUE TO THE FOUNDATIONS, THE MRP WILL BE BASED ON COMPARISON TO SIMILAR INTERNAL BENCHMARKED POSITIONS.
